{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532494"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:27:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:27:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14685"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14685"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.04,0.08,0.53,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7378"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111647"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7378"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14685"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93715"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1328"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"2777"},{"type":"tags","id":"3066"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18005"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25048"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45446"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111647"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of progressively worsening exertional dyspnoea. He reports that his symptoms have gradually worsened, and he now becomes breathless after walking one block. He has also noticed occasional palpitations. He has no other significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He works as a bartender and lives alone. On further questioning, he volunteers a history of regular cocaine use for the past eight years, typically using two to three times per week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears anxious but cooperative. His pulse rate is 110/min and irregular, blood pressure 165/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. He is diaphoretic. Cardiovascular examination reveals a displaced apex beat with a third heart sound. Chest auscultation reveals fine bibasal crepitations. His electrocardiogram shows left bundle branch block. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying pathophysiological mechanism for his cardiac dysfunction?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Calcium-dependent cardiotoxicity","Direct viral myocarditis","Coronary atherosclerosis","Catecholamine-induced necrosis","Autoimmune myocarditis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of cardiac dysfunction in the setting of chronic cocaine use. The clinical features (displaced apex, third heart sound, bibasal crepitations) and ECG changes suggest dilated cardiomyopathy. The three-month history of progressive symptoms in the context of eight years of regular cocaine use points to chronic rather than acute pathology. Understanding the mechanism is crucial for appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium-dependent cardiotoxicity\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism of cocaine-induced cardiomyopathy. Cocaine causes sustained elevation of intracellular calcium through multiple pathways, including increased sympathetic stimulation and direct effects on calcium channels. This leads to mitochondrial dysfunction, oxidative stress, and myocyte death. The chronic calcium overload triggers maladaptive cardiac remodeling and fibrosis. The progressive nature of symptoms over months in this long-term user supports this chronic mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect viral myocarditis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause dilated cardiomyopathy but would not typically show this strong temporal relationship with cocaine use. While cocaine users may be at increased risk of viral infections, this is not the primary mechanism of cardiac injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoronary atherosclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E, while accelerated in cocaine users, typically causes regional wall motion abnormalities rather than global dysfunction. The patient\u0027s age and the diffuse nature of his cardiac dysfunction make this less likely to be the primary mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECatecholamine-induced necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E, while contributing to acute cocaine cardiotoxicity, is not the predominant mechanism in chronic cardiomyopathy. This mechanism is more commonly associated with acute presentations immediately following cocaine use, rather than the progressive symptoms over months seen in this patient. The timeline clearly indicates chronic pathology rather than acute catecholamine excess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune myocarditis\u003C/strong\u003E has been reported in cocaine users but is relatively rare. The consistent temporal relationship with cocaine use and the absence of other autoimmune features make this mechanism less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these mechanisms is important as it influences management strategies. While cessation of cocaine use is crucial, treatments targeting calcium homeostasis and oxidative stress may be beneficial in these patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic cocaine use can cause dilated cardiomyopathy through multiple mechanisms including direct cardiotoxicity, increased sympathetic drive, and oxidative stress.","Long-term cocaine use leads to structural cardiac remodeling independent of coronary artery disease.","The risk of cocaine-induced cardiomyopathy is dose and duration-dependent, with significant changes typically occurring after 5-10 years of regular use."],"references":["Arenas DJ, Beltran S, Zhou S, Goldberg LR. Cocaine, cardiomyopathy, and heart failure: a systematic review and meta-analysis. Scientific Reports. 2020 Nov 13;10(1):19795. Available from: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-020-76273-1","Havakuk O, Rezkalla SH, Kloner RA. The Cardiovascular Effects of Cocaine. J Am Coll Cardiol. 2017 Jul 4;70(1):101-113. Available from: https://www.jacc.org/doi/10.1016/j.jacc.2017.05.014"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93715"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14685"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93715"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-17T16:56:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-17T16:56:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7378"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111647"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"hea